{"title_page": "Rungrado 1st of May Stadium", "text_new": "{{short description|Stadium in Pyongyang, North Korea}}\n{{Infobox venue\n| stadium_name = Rungrado 1st of May Stadium\n| fullname = The Rungrado 1st of May Stadium Pyongyang\n| image = Views from Yanggakdo International Hotel 10.JPG\n| location = [[R\u016dngrado|Rungra Island]], {{nowrap|[[Pyongyang]], [[North Korea]]}}\n| coordinates = {{Coord|39|2|58|N|125|46|31|E|region:KP_type:landmark_scale:3700|display=inline,title}}\n| broke_ground =\n| built =\n| opened = {{Start date|1989|05|01|df=y}}\n| closed = \n| demolished =\n| owner =\n| surface = Artificial turf<ref>{{cite web|title=North Korea: Rungrado May Day to undergo thorough revamp|url=http://stadiumdb.com/news/2013/09/north_korea_rungrado_may_day_to_undergo_thorough_revamp|website=Stadium DB|accessdate=21 July 2017}}</ref>\n| architect =\n| dimensions = Main pitch \u2013 {{convert|22500|m2|sqft|abbr=on}}<br />Total floor space \u2013 over {{convert|207000|m2|sqft|abbr=on}} | tenants = [[North Korea national football team]]<br />[[North Korea women's national football team]]<br/>[[April 25 Sports Club]]\n| image_size = 250\n| alt = \n| construction_cost =\n| former_names =\n| seating_capacity = 114,000\n}}\n{{Infobox Korean name\n|context=north\n|img=\n|caption=\n|hangul={{linktext|\ub989|\ub77c|\ub3c4}} 5{{linktext|\uc6d4}}1{{linktext|\uc77c| \uacbd\uae30\uc7a5}}\n|hanja={{linktext|\u7dbe|\u7f85|\u5cf6| \u4e94|\u6708|\u4e00|\u65e5| \u7af6\u6280\u5834}}\n|rr=Neungnado 5(o)-wol 1(ir)-il Gyeonggijang\n|mr=R\u016dngrado Ow\u014fl Iril Ky\u014fnggijang\n}}[[File:Arirang Mass Games 01.JPG|thumb|Exterior of Rungrado May Day Stadium]]\n[[File:Arirang Mass Games 12.JPG|thumb|[[Arirang Festival]], on the occasion of the 100th Anniversary of the birth of [[Kim Il-sung]].]]\n\nThe '''Rungrado 1st of May Stadium''', also known as the '''May Day Stadium''', is a [[multi-purpose stadium]] in [[R\u016dngrado|Rungra Island]], [[Pyongyang]], [[North Korea]] which was opened on 1 May 1989     . Its first major event was the [[13th World Festival of Youth and Students]]. It is the [[list of stadiums by capacity|largest stadium in the world]], with a total capacity of approximately 114,000. The site occupies an area of {{convert|20.7|ha|acre}}.\n\n==Uses==\nIt is currently used for [[Association football|football]] matches, a few [[sport of athletics|athletics]] events, but most often for the [[mass games]] of the [[Arirang Festival]]. Officially by North Korean claims the stadium supposedly has a capacity of 150,000 people, but the real capacity is under 114,000. Even with the lower actual capacity ranks, the stadium still ranks first on the [[List of stadiums by capacity|list of largest stadiums by capacity in the world]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-lineups.com/stadium/460/|title=Rungrado 1st of May Stadium \u2013 Football Stadium|work=Football-Lineups|accessdate=26 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Design==\nIts scalloped roof features 16 [[arch]]es arranged in a ring, and resembles a [[magnolia]] blossom. It hosts events on a main pitch covering {{convert|22500|m2|sqft|abbr=on}}. Its total floor space is over {{convert|207000|m2|sqft|abbr=on}} across eight storeys, and the lobes of its roof peak at more than {{convert|60|m|ft|abbr=on}} from the ground.{{fact|date=April 2020}}\n\n==History==\nAfter the [[1988 Summer Olympics]] had been awarded to [[Seoul]], North Korea doubled down its efforts to present itself as the legitimate Korean state. As part of these efforts, it successfully bid to organize the [[13th World Festival of Youth and Students]] in Pyongyang in 1989. Massive construction projects were initiated in preparation for the festival, one of which was the Rungrado 1st of May Stadium. At the time of completion, it was the largest stadium ever built in Asia.<ref name=\"Cha2012\">{{cite book|last=Cha|first=Victor|title=The Impossible State: North Korea, Past and Future|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AShswwfIbqsC&pg=PA120|year=2012|publisher=Random House|location=London|isbn=978-1-4481-3958-3|page=120}}</ref>\n\nWhile the stadium is used for sporting events, it is more frequently the site of massive performances and shows celebrating [[Kim Il-sung]] and the North Korean nation. In June\u2013July 2002 it was the site of a large choreographed \"[[Arirang Festival]]\" gymnastic and artistic performance. The extravaganza involved for the first time over 100,000 participants\u2014double the number of spectators,<ref name=\"guardian20020517\">{{cite news|last=Watts|first=Jonathan|url=https://www.theguardian.com/korea/article/0,2763,717149,00.html|title=Despair, hunger and defiance at the heart of the greatest show on earth|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=17 May 2002 | location=London}}</ref> and was open to foreigners. These performances are now an annual feature in Pyongyang, usually in August and September. The event in 2007 was recognized by the [[Guinness Book of Records]] as the largest gymnastic display with 100,090 participants.<ref>http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/largest-gymnastic-display</ref>\n\nIn 2000 Kim Jong-il entertained [[Madeleine Albright]], the [[United States Secretary of State]] under President [[Bill Clinton]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Is Kim her next challenge?|url=http://www.atimes.com/atimes/Korea/ML06Dg01.html|work=Asia Times Online|accessdate=31 December 2011}}</ref> ''[[Collision in Korea]]'' was the largest [[professional wrestling]] pay-per-view event ever that was jointly produced by [[World Championship Wrestling]] and [[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]. It took place over a period of two days on April 28 and 29, 1995 at the stadium and had an attendance of 150,000 and 190,000 according to local authorities. It did not air in North America until August 4, 1995. American wrestling journalist Dave Meltzer has claimed that the actual combined attendance for the two-day-event was somewhere around 160,000 total.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://whatculture.com/wwe/16-ppvs-not-on-the-wwe-network?page=5 |title=16 PPVs NOT On The WWE Network \u2013 Page 5 |publisher=Whatculture.com |date=2014-07-17 |accessdate=2016-05-26}}</ref>\n\nAfter a two-year renovation project, the stadium reopened in 2015. In July 2017, the Rungrado Stadium played host to six group stage matches as part of [[2018 AFC U-23 Championship qualification]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Schedule & Results|url=http://www.the-afc.com/afcasfeeds?view=all&id=202&type=Stage#ui-tabs-1|website=Asian Football Confederation|accessdate=23 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[September 2018 inter-Korean summit]] in Pyongyang, President [[Moon Jae-in]] of South Korea gave a speech with Chairman [[Kim Jong-un]] to 150,000{{dubious|date=August 2019}} North Korean spectators. The speech has themes of unification, peace, and cooperation.<ref>{{YouTube|id=hJod7qg2GCc|title=S. Korean President Moon Jae-in delivered public speech in front of some 150,000 Pyeongyang citizens}} published Sep 19, 2018 [[Arirang News]]</ref>\n\n==Notable events==\n*Opening and closing ceremonies of the [[13th World Festival of Youth and Students]] in 1989\n*[[Collision in Korea]] professional wrestling event in 1995\n*[[September 2018 inter-Korean summit|2018 Inter-Korean Summit Pyeongyang]]\n\n===Annual events===\n*[[Arirang Festival]]\n*[[Pyongyang Marathon]]\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|North Korea|Sport}}\n* [[List of football stadiums in North Korea]]\n* [[Strahov Stadium]]\n* [[Yanggakdo Stadium]]\n \n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|R\u016dngrado May First Stadium|R\u016dngnado Stadium}}\n* [http://www.dprk360.com/360/rungrado_may_day_stadium/ Rungnado May Day Stadium 360 degree panorama]\n* [https://maps.google.com/maps?q=Pyongyang,+North+Korea&hl=en&ie=UTF8&ll=39.049535,125.775089&spn=0.005141,0.00912&sll=37.0625,-95.677068&sspn=42.766543,74.707031&oq=pyongyang&hnear=P'y%C5%8Fngyang,+Pyongyang,+North+Korea&t=h&z=17 Rungnado May Day Stadium view from above]\n{{Stadiums in North Korea}}\n\n[[Category:1989 establishments in North Korea]]\n[[Category:Athletics (track and field) venues in North Korea]]\n[[Category:Event venues established in 1989]]\n[[Category:Football venues in North Korea]]\n[[Category:Multi-purpose stadiums in North Korea]]\n[[Category:National stadiums|North Korea]]\n[[Category:Sports venues completed in 1989]]\n[[Category:Sports venues in Pyongyang]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Stadium in Pyongyang, North Korea}}\n{{Infobox venue\n| stadium_name = Rungrado 1st of May Stadium\n| fullname = The Rungrado 1st of May Stadium Pyongyang\n| image = Views from Yanggakdo International Hotel 10.JPG\n| location = [[R\u016dngrado|Rungra Island]], {{nowrap|[[Pyongyang]], [[North Korea]]}}\n| coordinates = {{Coord|39|2|58|N|125|46|31|E|region:KP_type:landmark_scale:3700|display=inline,title}}\n| broke_ground =\n| built =\n| opened = {{Start date|1989|05|01|df=y}}\n| closed = \n| demolished =\n| owner =\n| surface = Artificial turf<ref>{{cite web|title=North Korea: Rungrado May Day to undergo thorough revamp|url=http://stadiumdb.com/news/2013/09/north_korea_rungrado_may_day_to_undergo_thorough_revamp|website=Stadium DB|accessdate=21 July 2017}}</ref>\n| architect =\n| dimensions = Main pitch \u2013 {{convert|22500|m2|sqft|abbr=on}}<br />Total floor space \u2013 over {{convert|207000|m2|sqft|abbr=on}} | tenants = [[North Korea national football team]]<br />[[North Korea women's national football team]]<br/>[[April 25 Sports Club]]\n| image_size = 250\n| alt = \n| construction_cost =\n| former_names =\n| seating_capacity = 114,000\n}}\n{{Infobox Korean name\n|context=north\n|img=\n|caption=\n|hangul={{linktext|\ub989|\ub77c|\ub3c4}} 5{{linktext|\uc6d4}}1{{linktext|\uc77c| \uacbd\uae30\uc7a5}}\n|hanja={{linktext|\u7dbe|\u7f85|\u5cf6| \u4e94|\u6708|\u4e00|\u65e5| \u7af6\u6280\u5834}}\n|rr=Neungnado 5(o)-wol 1(ir)-il Gyeonggijang\n|mr=R\u016dngrado Ow\u014fl Iril Ky\u014fnggijang\n}}[[File:Arirang Mass Games 01.JPG|thum